<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,1118]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,560,295,323]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Description of 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[390,405,295,309]" fontSize="6" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">rd</superScript>
instar larva.
</emphasis>
Size 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[624,633,298,323]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">(</emphasis>
based on 
<specimenCount box="[740,899,298,323]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="generic">24 specimens</specimenCount>
): BL 
<quantity box="[961,1079,298,323]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.06" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="10.6">10.60 mm</quantity>
; HL 3.00 mm (2.41–3.33), HW 
<quantity box="[151,252,334,359]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="2.45">2.45 mm</quantity>
(2.22–2.72), ML 
<quantity box="[456,558,334,359]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="2.54">2.54 mm</quantity>
(2.24–2.76), HW/HL 0.82, ML/HL 0.85. General colouring dark brown with darker markings, abdomen with a dorsal median stripe with a characteristic pattern (
<figureCitation box="[1118,1216,370,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="24.[151,249,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[239,1331,206,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-43@24.[224,1338,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distoleon tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798), 3rd instar larva (France: Gard, Générac). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–e: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909405/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 12c</figureCitation>
), ventral side paler with dark brown markings; head capsule dark brown, lateral and ventral sides with extensive dark markings (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="24.[151,249,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[239,1331,206,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-43@24.[224,1338,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distoleon tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798), 3rd instar larva (France: Gard, Générac). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–e: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909405/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 12d</figureCitation>
); mandibles dark brown; legs yellowish or whitish; setae of the body black. Head longer than wide; mandibles comparatively strong, shorter than the head capsule (
<figureCitation box="[788,891,478,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="24.[151,249,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[239,1331,206,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-43@24.[224,1338,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distoleon tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798), 3rd instar larva (France: Gard, Générac). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–e: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909405/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 12a</figureCitation>
); interdental mandibular setae: (3–4)(1)(1)(0). Pronotum covered by large setae interspersed with short bristles (
<figureCitation box="[917,1019,514,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[241,1323,508,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-216@11.[233,1335,499,1910]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pronotum of 3rd instar larvae of Dendroleontini and Nemoleontini; A, Dendroleon pantherinus; B, Nemoleon notatus; C, Distoleon tetragrammicus; D, Creoleon lugdunensis; E, Neuroleon nemausiensis; F, Macronemurus appendiculatus; G, Megistopus lucasi; H, Gymnocnemia variegata. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909373/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs. 4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1034,1080,514,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="24.[151,249,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[239,1331,206,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-43@24.[224,1338,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distoleon tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798), 3rd instar larva (France: Gard, Générac). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–e: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909405/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">12b</figureCitation>
). Mesothoracic and abdominal spiracles brown. VIII abdominal sternite with odontoid processes; IX sternite with a ventral pair of spiniform setae and with two small rastra each equipped with 4 sub-equal digging setae (
<figureCitation box="[966,1064,586,611]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,249,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[231,1357,197,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-239@10.[188,1398,193,1584]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. IX and VIII abdominal sternite of 3rd instar larva of Dendroleontini and Nemoleontini. A, Dendroleon pantherinus; B, Nemoleon notatus; C, Distoleon tetragrammicus; D, Creoleon lugdunensis; E, Neuroleon assimilis; F, Macronemurus appendiculatus; G, Megistopus lucasi; H, Gymnocnemia variegata. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909369/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs. 3C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1076,1120,586,611]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="24.[151,249,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[239,1331,206,1934]" captionTargetId="figure-43@24.[224,1338,195,1940]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distoleon tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798), 3rd instar larva (France: Gard, Générac). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–e: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909405/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">12e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,1118]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,622,647]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Bio-ecology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[350,562,624,647]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetragrammicus">
<emphasis box="[350,562,624,647]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. tetragrammicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an euryoecious species and its larvae are able to colonize any microhabitat with presence of dry and fine substratum, thus it is very abundant and widespread. In southern Europe it is found from coastal dunes to montane forests, in a large array of habitats, always in dry conditions even if punctiform. The larvae appear avoid exposed sites, preferring protected niches such as at the base of trees or shrubs, under rocks or in their proximity. Therefore they are absent from open coastal sand dunes while they are common on back dunes with conspicuous vegetation growing. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[611,829,803,826]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetragrammicus">
<emphasis box="[611,829,803,826]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. tetragrammicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae are frequent in rocky microhabitat such as escarpments or under overhangs and they are able to colonize similar artificial structures, such as stone walls.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1300,874,899]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,1118]" box="[199,1300,874,899]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,874,899]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution.</emphasis>
Widespread in the western Palaearctic, only avoiding cold climates and true deserts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,1118]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,910,935]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks.</emphasis>
The larva of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[464,676,912,935]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetragrammicus">
<emphasis box="[464,676,912,935]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. tetragrammicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Acevedo et al." authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[822,966,910,935]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[822,966,910,935]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only other European congener, for its overall dark brown colouring and pattern while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Acevedo et al." authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[700,846,946,971]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annulatus">
<emphasis box="[700,846,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. annulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much paler, sand-like in colour, with contrasting dark markings (
<bibRefCitation author="Acevedo, F. &amp; Monserrat, V. J. &amp; Badano, D." box="[328,562,982,1007]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="488 - 494" refId="ref38342" refString="Acevedo, F., Monserrat, V. J. &amp; Badano, D. (2013) The larvae of the two European species of genus Distoleon: D. annulatus (Klug, 1834) and D. tetragrammicus (Fabricius, 1798). A comparative description (Insecta, Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Zootaxa, 3721, 488 - 494." type="journal article" year="2013">
Acevedo 
<emphasis box="[437,494,982,1007]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
). The pigmentation pattern of the dorsal side of the abdomen, composed by a median series of contiguous circular markings is a constant character in this species allowing the identification of all larval stages of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[363,574,1056,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Distoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetragrammicus">
<emphasis box="[363,574,1056,1079]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">D. tetragrammicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, the relatively conspicuous size of this antlion permits an immediate distinction of the 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[362,375,1090,1104]" fontSize="6" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">rd</superScript>
instar larvae from the other known member of the tribe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
